  {
    "id": "UgyRpJy6W52K764TyYB4AaABAg",
    "author": "@aquahoodjd",
    "author_channel_id": "UCEpkbKLb0ELWtD9jh2m52OA",
    "text": "Hi how are you doing I have a question? What do you think about using very heavy and robust springs and flywheels to store solar energy as opposed to pumping water and big open circuit systems and dropping weights down on mine shaft when you could pack this into a pretty compact package and could you scale that commercially do you think?\n\nI really like the idea of wind and wind as a supplement to solar is a fantastic idea You could also pull heat out of the solar panels and I believe by doing so it makes them more efficient and you could potentially pull a certain amount of harvestable energy out of that heat if you run a closed circuit loop of water and a cooling tower to bleed off the hot temperature from the back of solar panels or to even heat or preheat the water that's going into your own hot water heater or a commercial hot water heater which would save energy but it's harder to quantify that....",
    "likes": 0,
    "published_at": "2025-03-06T07:54:11Z",
    "reply_count": 3,
    "replies": [
      {
        "id": "UgyRpJy6W52K764TyYB4AaABAg.AFJvR82SVzMAFKZ7xijyQI",
        "author": "@ThinkingandTinkering",
        "author_channel_id": "UC4AkVj-qnJxNtKuz3rkq16A",
        "text": "yeah it's gravity storage mate and flywheels are used - springs tend to be a bit limiting just because of their nature",
        "likes": 0,
        "published_at": "2025-03-06T13:49:50Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "UgyRpJy6W52K764TyYB4AaABAg.AFJvR82SVzMAFPJc6A_1AD",
        "author": "@aquahoodjd",
        "author_channel_id": "UCEpkbKLb0ELWtD9jh2m52OA",
        "text": "@ThinkingandTinkering  so you think the springs are a bit limiting on the efficiency to the point of making it inefficient and impossible or do you think that you could design one that is actually scalable? It would be nice because it's very simple and could be much more compact than let's say these other ideas such as lakes,  hydro, and buildings with blocks. It also escapes the problem of battery chemistry and the need or seemingly the need to use a lot of environmentally destructive chemicals?",
        "likes": 0,
        "published_at": "2025-03-08T10:10:28Z"
      },
      {
        "id": "UgyRpJy6W52K764TyYB4AaABAg.AFJvR82SVzMAFPK0tGMMmW",
        "author": "@aquahoodjd",
        "author_channel_id": "UCEpkbKLb0ELWtD9jh2m52OA",
        "text": "@ThinkingandTinkering  It seems to me it's a pretty simple concept It's keeping it simple. I think a lot of would have to do with the type of gearing that you use what metal you use for the springs how it's arranged, and the drag on your flywheels how much you could reduce it? It has to of course turn a generator to feed power back into the grid but other than that energy output efficiency everywhere else where possible. I wonder if a well-balanced mass perhaps circular of course, and horizontal to the ground with as little resistance on its spin as possible so either maglev using some cold gases or a very well balanced extremely durable top type of configuration?",
        "likes": 0,
        "published_at": "2025-03-08T10:14:00Z"
      }
    ]
  },
